Definition 1.8. An object $A$ of $\mathbb{C}$ is said be cauchy-complete if for every $Y$ in $\mathbb{C}$ and formulas $L$ in $P(Y\times A)$ and $R$ in $P(A\times Y)$ satisfying $\delta_{Y}(y,y^{\prime})\leq\exists a:A.\ (L(y,a)\wedge R(a,y^{\prime}))$ $\exists y:Y.\ (R(a,y)\wedge L(y,a^{\prime}))\leq\delta_{A}(a,a^{\prime})$ there exists a morphism $g:Y\longrightarrow A$ such that $\delta_{A}(g(y),a)=L(y,a)$.
Definition 2.5. A regular doctrine $(\mathbb{C},P)$ is said to be higher order if it has power objects and, for every object $A$ of the base, $\{\delta_{A}\}:A\longrightarrow\mathbb{P}(A)$ is an internally injective morphism with image, such that for every morphism $g:Y\longrightarrow\mathbb{P}(A)$ it holds that $\exists a:A.\ (\{\delta_{A}\}(a),g(y))=\top_{Y}(y)$ if and only if $\exists a:A.\ a\in_{A}g(y)=\top_{Y}(y)\ \ \ \text{and}\ \ \ a\in_{A}g(y)\wedge a% ^{\prime}\in_{A}g(y)\leq\delta_{A}(a,a^{\prime})$
Definition 1.7. An object $A$ of $\mathbb{C}$ is said to satisfy AUC, if for every $Y$ in $\mathbb{C}$ and formula $F$ in $P(Y\times A)$ satisfying $F(y,a)\wedge F(y,a^{\prime})\leq\delta_{A}(a,a^{\prime})$ $\top_{A}=\exists y:Y.\ F(y,a)$ there exists a unique morphism $f:Y\longrightarrow A$ such that $\delta_{A}(f(y),a)=F(y,a)$.
Definition 1.1. A doctrine is a pair $(\mathbb{C},P)$ where $\mathbb{C}$ is a category with binary products and $P$ a functor $P:\mathbb{C}^{op}\longrightarrow\textbf{ISL}$
Definition 1.5. In a regular doctrine $(\mathbb{C},P)$ an object $A$ of $\mathbb{C}$ is a $P$-sheaf if for every span in $\mathbb{C}$ of the form $\xymatrix{Y&X\ar[l]_{-}{d}\ar[r]^{-}{q}&A}$ with $d$ internally bijective, there exists a unique $h:Y\longrightarrow A$ with $h\circ d=q$.
Definition 2.3. A $\mathcal{V}$-category $\mathcal{K}$ is said to be fibrant if each hom-object $\mathcal{K}(A,B)$ is fibrant in $\mathcal{V}$.
Definition 6.1. An object $K$ of a locally cofibrant and fibrant $\mathcal{V}$-category $\mathcal{K}$ is called homotopy $\lambda$-presentable when $\mathcal{K}(K,-)\colon\mathcal{K}\to\operatorname{Int}\mathcal{V}$ preserves homotopy $\lambda$-filtered colimits.
Definition 6.9. Let $\mathcal{V}$ be a monoidal model category having all objects cofibrant. Then a fibrant $\mathcal{V}$-category $\mathcal{K}$ will be called homotopy locally $\lambda$-presentable provided that it has weighted homotopy colimits and has a set $\mathcal{A}$ of homotopy $\lambda$-presentable objects such that every object of $\mathcal{K}$ is a homotopy $\lambda$-filtered colimit of objects from $\mathcal{A}$. $\mathcal{K}$ is called homotopy locally presentable when it is homotopy locally $\lambda$-presentable for some regular cardinal $\lambda$.
Definition 4.2. Let $\mathcal{V}$ be a monoidal model category satisfying the monoid axiom, $\mathcal{K}$ a fibrant $\mathcal{V}$-category, $D\colon\mathcal{D}\to\mathcal{K}$ a diagram, and $G\colon\mathcal{D}^{\textnormal{op}}\to\mathcal{V}$ a weight. Let $G_{c}\colon\mathcal{D}^{\textnormal{op}}\to\mathcal{V}$ be a cofibrant replacement of $G$ in the projective model category structure. Then a homotopy colimit of $D$ weighted by $G$ is an object $G\ast_{h}D$ equipped with a natural transformation $\beta\colon\mathcal{K}(G\ast_{h}D,-)\to[\mathcal{D}^{\textnormal{op}},\mathcal% {V}](G_{c},\mathcal{K}(D,-))$ whose components are weak equivalences.
Definition 5.4. Let $\mathcal{K}$ be a full subcategory of a category $\mathcal{M}$. We say that a full subcategory $\mathcal{A}$ of $\mathcal{K}$ is $\mathcal{M}$-accessibly embedded in $\mathcal{K}$ when there exists a regular cardinal $\lambda$ such that $\mathcal{A}$ is closed in $\mathcal{K}$ under all $\lambda$-filtered colimits which exist in $\mathcal{K}$ and are preserved by the inclusion into $\mathcal{M}$. In this case, we say that $\mathcal{K}$ is $(\mathcal{M},\lambda)$-accessibly embedded in $\mathcal{K}$.
Definition 2.1. Let $\mathcal{V}$ be a monoidal model category and $\mathcal{K}$ a $\mathcal{V}$-category. The homotopy category $\operatorname{ho}\mathcal{K}$ of $\mathcal{K}$ has the same objects as $\mathcal{K}$, and $\operatorname{ho}\mathcal{K}(A,B)=U(\mathcal{K}(A,B))$. There is an induced functor $p_{*}$ from the underlying ordinary category $\mathcal{K}_{0}$ of $\mathcal{K}$ to $\operatorname{ho}\mathcal{K}$, sending a morphism $f\colon I\to\mathcal{K}(A,B)$ to $p(f)$. A morphism $f\colon A\to B$ in a $\mathcal{V}$-category $\mathcal{K}$ is called a homotopy equivalence if its image in $\operatorname{ho}\mathcal{K}$ is invertible.
Definition 5.2. Let $\mathcal{K}$ be a fibrant $\mathcal{V}$-category. A full subcategory $\mathcal{A}$ of $\mathcal{K}$ is called homotopy replete if an object $D$ in $\mathcal{K}$ lies in $\mathcal{A}$ whenever there is a homotopy equivalence $h\colon C\to D$ with $C$ in $\mathcal{A}$.
Definition 6.4. A $\lambda$-small ordinary category $\mathcal{D}$ will be called genuinely $\lambda$-small when the weight $\overline{\Delta I}\colon\overline{\mathcal{D}}\to\mathcal{V}$ has a $\lambda$-presentable cofibrant replacement $G\colon\overline{\mathcal{D}}\to\mathcal{V}$.
Definition 3.4. Let $\mathcal{L}$ be a full sub-$\mathcal{V}$-category of a fibrant $\mathcal{V}$-category $\mathcal{K}$. We say that $\mathcal{L}$ is homotopy reflective in $\mathcal{K}$ if, for each $K$ in $\mathcal{K}$, there is $\eta_{K}\colon K\to K^{\ast}$ with $K^{\ast}$ in $\mathcal{L}$ such that each $L$ in $\mathcal{L}$ is homotopy orthogonal to $\eta_{K}$.
Definition 3.1. Let $\mathcal{V}$ be a monoidal model category, $\mathcal{K}$ a $\mathcal{V}$-category, and $f\colon A\to B$ a morphism in $\mathcal{K}$. Then an object $K$ in $\mathcal{K}$ is called homotopy orthogonal to $f$ if $\mathcal{K}(f,K)$ is a weak equivalence.
Definition 4.7. Let $F\colon\mathcal{K}\to\mathcal{L}$ be a $\mathcal{V}$-functor between fibrant $\mathcal{V}$-categories, $G\colon\mathcal{D}^{\textnormal{op}}\to\mathcal{K}$ a cofibrant weight, and $D\colon\mathcal{D}\to\mathcal{K}$ a diagram. We say that $F$ preserves the homotopy weighted colimit $G\ast_{h}D$ when $F(G\ast_{h}D)$ is $G\ast_{h}FD$ with a homotopy colimit cocone $G\xrightarrow{\quad\delta\quad}\mathcal{K}(D,G\ast_{h}D)\xrightarrow{\quad% \quad}\mathcal{L}(FD,F(G\ast_{h}D)).$
Definition 5.8. A full subcategory of a fibrant $\mathcal{V}$-category is called homotopy accessibly embedded when it is closed under homotopy $\lambda$-filtered colimits for some regular cardinal $\lambda$.
Definition 2.3. Let $f\colon G\to H$ be a group homomorphism. A morphism $\theta\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha\colon G\!\curvearrowright\!X\to H\!% \curvearrowright\!Y$ is $f$-equivariant if it satisfies $\theta_{x}=f$ for any $x\in X$. In this case, we simply write the morphism as $f\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha$. When $f=\mathrm{id}_{G}$, we say the morphism is equivariant, or $G$-equivariant if we specify the group $G$, and denote it by $G\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha\colon G\!\curvearrowright\!X\to G\!% \curvearrowright\!Y$. In this case, $\alpha$ is nothing but a usual $G$-map $\alpha\colon X\to Y$.
Definition 5.30. An object $F$ in $\mathit{Add}(\mathrm{Sp},\mathit{Set})$ $($resp. $\mathit{Add}(\mathcal{T},\mathit{Set}))$ is called deflative if for any stab-surjective 1-cell $\alpha\colon G\!\curvearrowright\!X\to H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$, $F([H\!\curvearrowright\!Y\overset{\alpha}{\longleftarrow}G\!\curvearrowright\!% X\overset{\alpha}{\longrightarrow}H\!\curvearrowright\!Y])=\mathrm{id}_{F(H\!% \curvearrowright\!Y)}$ holds. We denote the full subcategory of deflative objects by $\mathit{Add}_{\mathrm{dfl}}(\mathrm{Sp},\mathit{Set})$ $($resp. $\mathit{Add}_{\mathrm{dfl}}(\mathcal{T},\mathit{Set}))$.
Definition 5.14. For any 1-cell $\alpha\colon G\!\curvearrowright\!X\to H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$ in $\mathbb{S}$, we define the classes $\mathbf{R}_{\alpha}$ and $\mathbf{T}_{\alpha}$ by $\displaystyle\mathbf{R}_{\alpha}$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle[G\!\curvearrowright\!X\overset{\mathrm{id}}{\longleftarrow}G\!% \curvearrowright\!X\overset{\alpha}{\longrightarrow}H\!\curvearrowright\!Y]% \quad(\text{in}\ \mathrm{Span}^{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}_{H\!\curvearrowright\!% Y}),$ $\displaystyle\mathbf{T}_{\alpha}$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle[H\!\curvearrowright\!Y\overset{\alpha}{\longleftarrow}G\!% \curvearrowright\!X\overset{\mathrm{id}}{\longrightarrow}G\!\curvearrowright\!% X]\quad(\text{in}\ \mathrm{Span}^{H\!\curvearrowright\!Y}_{G\!\curvearrowright% \!X}).$
Definition 2.16. Let $\alpha\colon G\!\curvearrowright\!X\to H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$ be a 1-cell. (1) $\alpha$ is an equivalence if there is a 1-cell $\beta\colon H\!\curvearrowright\!Y\to G\!\curvearrowright\!X$ and 2-cells $\rho\colon\beta\circ\alpha\Rightarrow\mathrm{id}_{G\!\curvearrowright\!X},\ \ % \lambda\colon\alpha\circ\beta\Rightarrow\mathrm{id}_{H\!\curvearrowright\!Y}.$ $\beta$ is called a quasi-inverse of $\alpha$. (2) $\alpha$ is an adjoint equivalence if there is a 2-cell $\beta$ and 2-cells $\rho,\lambda$ as above, which moreover satisfy $\alpha\circ\rho=\lambda\circ\alpha,\ \ \rho\circ\beta=\beta\circ\lambda$ in the diagram $\xy(-40,0)*+{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}="0";(-20,0)*+{H\!\curvearrowright\!Y}="2"% ;(0,0)*+{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}="4";(20,0)*+{H\!\curvearrowright\!Y}="6";(40,% 0)*+{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}="8";{\ar^{\alpha}"0";"2"};{\ar^{\beta}"2";"4"};{% \ar_{\alpha}"4";"6"};{\ar^{\beta}"6";"8"};{\ar@/_{1}.8pc/_{\mathrm{id}}"0";"4"% };{\ar@/^{1}.8pc/^{\mathrm{id}}"2";"6"};{\ar@/_{1}.8pc/_{\mathrm{id}}"4";"8"};% {\ar@{=>}^{\rho}(-20,-3);(-20,-6)};{\ar@{=>}^{\lambda}(0,3);(0,6)};{\ar@{=>}^{% \rho}(20,-3);(20,-6)};\endxy.$ (3) $\alpha$ is an isomorphism if there is a 1-cell $\beta\colon H\!\curvearrowright\!Y\to G\!\curvearrowright\!X$ which satisfies $\beta\circ\alpha=\mathrm{id}_{G\!\curvearrowright\!X},\ \ \alpha\circ\beta=% \mathrm{id}_{H\!\curvearrowright\!Y}.$ This is equivalent to that $\alpha$ is an isomorphism in $\mathrm{GrSet}$. Remark that there are implications $(\text{isomorphism})\ \Rightarrow\ (\text{adjoint equivalence})\ \Rightarrow\ % (\text{equivalence}).$
Definition 5.6. A semi-Mackey functor $M$ on $\mathbb{S}$ is a Mackey functor if the monoid $M(G\!\curvearrowright\!X)$ is an additive group for any $G\!\curvearrowright\!X\in\mathbb{S}^{0}$. The full subcategory of Mackey functors in $\mathit{SMack}(\mathbb{S})$ is denoted by $\mathit{Mack}(\mathbb{S})$.
Definition 2.11. Let $G\!\curvearrowright\!X\overset{\theta\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha}{% \longrightarrow}H\!\curvearrowright\!Y\overset{\tau\!\curvearrowright\!\beta}{% \longrightarrow}K\!\curvearrowright\!Z$ be a sequence of 1-cells. (1) For a 2-cell $\xy(-14,0)*+{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}="0";(14,0)*+{H\!\curvearrowright\!Y}="2";% {\ar@/^{1}.2pc/^{\theta\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha}"0";"2"};{\ar@/_{1}.2pc/_{% \theta^{\prime}\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha^{\prime}}"0";"2"};{\ar@{=>}^{% \varepsilon}(0,2);(0,-2)};\endxy,$ define $(\tau\!\curvearrowright\!\beta)\circ\varepsilon\colon(\tau\!\curvearrowright\!% \beta)\circ(\theta\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha)\Rightarrow(\tau\!% \curvearrowright\!\beta)\circ(\theta^{\prime}\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha^{% \prime})$ by $((\tau\!\curvearrowright\!\beta)\circ\varepsilon)_{x}=\tau_{\alpha(x)}(% \varepsilon_{x})\quad(\forall x\in X).$ (2) For a 2-cell $\xy(-14,0)*+{H\!\curvearrowright\!Y}="0";(14,0)*+{K\!\curvearrowright\!Z}="2";% {\ar@/^{1}.2pc/^{\tau\!\curvearrowright\!\beta}"0";"2"};{\ar@/_{1}.2pc/_{\tau^% {\prime}\!\curvearrowright\!\beta^{\prime}}"0";"2"};{\ar@{=>}^{\delta}(0,2);(0% ,-2)};\endxy,$ define $\delta\circ(\theta\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha)\colon(\tau\!\curvearrowright\!% \beta)\circ(\theta\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha)\Rightarrow(\tau^{\prime}\!% \curvearrowright\!\beta^{\prime})\circ(\theta\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha)$ by $(\delta\circ(\theta\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha))_{x}=\delta_{\alpha(x)}\quad(% \forall x\in X).$
Definition 3.5. Let $\mathbb{C}$ be a 2-category with invertible 2-cells. For any $A_{1}$ and $A_{2}$ in $\mathbb{C}^{0}$, their 2-coproduct $(A_{1}\amalg A_{2},\iota_{1},\iota_{2})$ is defined to be a triplet of $A_{1}\amalg A_{2}\in\mathbb{C}^{0}$ and $\iota_{1}\in\mathbb{C}^{1}(A_{1},A_{1}\amalg A_{2}),\ \ \iota_{2}\in\mathbb{C}% ^{1}(A_{2},A_{1}\amalg A_{2}),$ satisfying the following conditions. (i) For any $X\in\mathbb{C}^{0}$ and $f_{i}\in\mathbb{C}^{1}(A_{i},X)\ (i=1,2)$, there exist $f\in\mathbb{C}^{1}(A_{1}\amalg A_{2},X)$ and $\xi_{i}\in\mathbb{C}^{2}(f\circ\iota_{i},f_{i})\ (i=1,2)$ as in the following diagram. $\xy(0,-6)*+{X}="0";(-18,10)*+{A_{1}}="2";(0,10)*+{A_{1}\amalg A_{2}}="4";(18,1% 0)*+{A_{2}}="6";{\ar_{f_{1}}"2";"0"};{\ar_{f}"4";"0"};{\ar^{f_{2}}"6";"0"};{% \ar^{(}0.4){\iota_{1}}"2";"4"};{\ar_{(}0.4){\iota_{2}}"6";"4"};{\ar@{=>}_{\xi_% {1}}(-4,6);(-7.5,3)};{\ar@{=>}^{\xi_{2}}(4,6);(7.5,3)};\endxy$ (ii) For any triplets $(f,\xi_{1},\xi_{2})$ and $(f^{\prime},\xi_{1}^{\prime},\xi_{2}^{\prime})$ as in (i), there exists a unique 2-cell $\eta\in\mathbb{C}^{2}(f,f^{\prime})$ such that $\xi_{i}^{\prime}\cdot(\eta\circ\iota_{i})=\xi_{i}\ (i=1,2)$, namely, the following diagram of 2-cells is commutative. $\xy(-10,6)*+{f\circ\iota_{i}}="0";(10,6)*+{f^{\prime}\circ\iota_{i}}="2";(0,-7% )*+{f_{i}}="4";(0,9)*+{}="6";{\ar@{=>}^{\eta\circ\iota_{i}}"0";"2"};{\ar@{=>}_% {\xi_{i}}"0";"4"};{\ar@{=>}^{\xi_{i}^{\prime}}"2";"4"};{\ar@{}|% \circlearrowright"6";"4"};\endxy$
Definition 5.22. Category $\mathcal{T}$ is defined as follows. (1) $\mathrm{Ob}(\mathcal{T})=\mathrm{Ob}(\mathrm{Sp})$. (2) For any objects $G\!\curvearrowright\!X,H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$ in $\mathcal{T}$, $\mathcal{T}(G\!\curvearrowright\!X,H\!\curvearrowright\!Y)=K_{0}(\mathrm{Sp}(G% \!\curvearrowright\!X,H\!\curvearrowright\!Y)).$ Thus a morphism $G\!\curvearrowright\!X\rightharpoonup H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$ in $\mathcal{T}$ is written as a difference $[S]-[T]\colon G\!\curvearrowright\!X\rightharpoonup H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$ of $[S],[T]\in\mathrm{Sp}(G\!\curvearrowright\!X,H\!\curvearrowright\!Y)$. Composition of morphisms is defined by extending the composition in $\mathrm{Sp}$ by linearity. Also in $\mathcal{T}$, $G\!\curvearrowright\!X\overset{\mathbf{R}_{\upsilon_{X}}}{\leftharpoonup}G\!% \curvearrowright\!X\amalg H\!\curvearrowright\!Y\overset{\mathbf{R}_{\upsilon_% {Y}}}{\rightharpoonup}H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$ gives a product of $G\!\curvearrowright\!X$ and $H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$.
Definition 4.10. Let $\alpha\colon G\!\curvearrowright\!X\to H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$ be any 1-cell in $\mathbb{S}$. (1) Define $\mathrm{SIm}\alpha=\mathrm{SIm}(\theta_{\alpha}\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha)\in% \mathrm{Ob}({}_{H}\mathit{set})$ by $\mathrm{SIm}\alpha=(H\times X)/\sim,$ where the relation $\sim$ is defined as follows. - $(\eta,x),(\eta^{\prime},x^{\prime})\in H\times X$ are equivalent if there exists $g\in G$ satisfying $x^{\prime}=gx\ \ \ \text{and}\ \ \ \eta=\eta^{\prime}\theta_{\alpha,x}(g).$ We denote the equivalence class of $(\eta,x)$ by $[\eta,x]$. The $H$-action on $\mathrm{SIm}\alpha$ is given by $h[\eta,x]=[h\eta,x].$ We call $\mathrm{SIm}\alpha$ the stabilizerwise image of $\alpha=\theta_{\alpha}\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha$. (2) Define a map $\upsilon_{\alpha}\colon X\to\mathrm{SIm}\alpha$ by $\upsilon_{\alpha}(x)=[e,x]\quad(\forall x\in X)$ and put $\theta_{\upsilon_{\alpha}}=\theta_{\alpha}$. Then $\upsilon_{\alpha}=(\theta_{\alpha}\!\curvearrowright\!\upsilon_{\alpha})\colon G% \!\curvearrowright\!X\to H\!\curvearrowright\!\mathrm{SIm}\alpha$ becomes a 1-cell.
Definition 6.2. Let $G,H$ be finite groups. For any $G$-$H$-biset $U$, we associate a span $S_{U}$ to $G\!\curvearrowright\!\mathrm{pt}$ from $H\!\curvearrowright\!\mathrm{pt}$ by $S_{U}=(G\!\curvearrowright\!\mathrm{pt}\overset{\mathrm{pr}^{(G)}\!% \curvearrowright\!\mathrm{pt}}{\longleftarrow}G\times H\!\curvearrowright\!U% \overset{\mathrm{pr}^{(H)}\!\curvearrowright\!\mathrm{pt}}{\longrightarrow}H\!% \curvearrowright\!\mathrm{pt}),$ where $\mathrm{pr}^{(G)}\colon G\times H\to G$ and $\mathrm{pr}^{(H)}\colon G\times H\to H$ are the projections.
Definition 5.18. Let $\displaystyle S$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle(H\!\curvearrowright\!Y\overset{\alpha_{S}}{\longleftarrow}L_{S}% \!\curvearrowright\!W_{S}\overset{\beta_{S}}{\longrightarrow}G\!% \curvearrowright\!X)\ \ \in(\mathrm{Span}^{H\!\curvearrowright\!Y}_{G\!% \curvearrowright\!X})^{0}$ $\displaystyle T$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle(K\!\curvearrowright\!Z\overset{\alpha_{T}}{\longleftarrow}L_{T}% \!\curvearrowright\!W_{T}\overset{\beta_{T}}{\longrightarrow}H\!% \curvearrowright\!Y)\ \ \in(\mathrm{Span}^{K\!\curvearrowright\!Z}_{H\!% \curvearrowright\!Y})^{0}$ be two consecutive spans in $\mathbb{S}$. We define their composition $T\circ S=(K\!\curvearrowright\!Z\overset{\alpha_{T\circ S}}{\longleftarrow}L_{% T\circ S}\!\curvearrowright\!W_{T\circ S}\overset{\beta_{T\circ S}}{% \longrightarrow}G\!\curvearrowright\!X)$ as follows. - Take a 2-fibered product $\xy(-14,7)*+{L_{T}\times L_{S}\!\curvearrowright\!F}="0";(14,7)*+{L_{S}\!% \curvearrowright\!W_{S}}="2";(-14,-7)*+{L_{T}\!\curvearrowright\!W_{T}}="4";(1% 4,-7)*+{H\!\curvearrowright\!Y}="6";{\ar^{(}0.56){\wp_{W_{S}}}"0";"2"};{\ar_{% \wp_{W_{T}}}"0";"4"};{\ar^{\alpha_{S}}"2";"6"};{\ar_{\beta_{T}}"4";"6"};{\ar@{% =>}^{\chi}(-2,0);(2,0)};\endxy$ and put $\displaystyle L_{T\circ S}=L_{T}\times L_{S}$ $\displaystyle,$ $\displaystyle W_{T\circ S}=F,$ $\displaystyle\alpha_{T\circ S}=\alpha_{T}\circ\wp_{W_{T}}$ $\displaystyle,$ $\displaystyle\beta_{T\circ S}=\beta_{S}\circ\wp_{W_{S}},$ as in the following diagram. $\xy(0,12)*+{L_{T\circ S}\!\curvearrowright\!W_{T\circ S}}="0";(-15,0)*+{L_{T}% \!\curvearrowright\!W_{T}}="2";(15,0)*+{L_{S}\!\curvearrowright\!W_{S}}="4";(-% 30,-12)*+{K\!\curvearrowright\!Z}="6";(0,-12)*+{H\!\curvearrowright\!Y}="8";(3% 0,-12)*+{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}="10";{\ar_{(}0.6){\wp_{W_{T}}}"0";"2"};{\ar^{% (}0.6){\wp_{W_{S}}}"0";"4"};{\ar_{(}0.6){\alpha_{T}}"2";"6"};{\ar_{(}0.4){% \beta_{T}}"2";"8"};{\ar^{(}0.4){\alpha_{S}}"4";"8"};{\ar^{(}0.6){\beta_{S}}"4"% ;"10"};{\ar@{=>}^{\chi}(-2,0);(2,0)};\endxy$
Definition 3.1. Let $\iota\colon H\hookrightarrow G$ be a monomorphism of groups. For any $X\in\mathrm{Ob}({}_{H}\mathit{set})$, we define $\mathrm{Ind}_{\iota}X\in\mathrm{Ob}({}_{G}\mathit{set})$ by $\mathrm{Ind}_{\iota}X=(G\times X)/\sim,$ where the equivalence relation $\sim$ is defined by - $(\xi,x)$ and $(\xi^{\prime},x^{\prime})$ in $G\times X$ are equivalent if there exists $h\in H$ satisfying $x^{\prime}=hx,\ \ \xi=\xi^{\prime}\iota(h).$ We denote the equivalence class of $(\xi,x)$ by $[\xi,x]\in\mathrm{Ind}_{\iota}X$. The $G$-action on $\mathrm{Ind}_{\iota}X$ is defined by $g[\xi,x]=[g\xi,x]$ for any $g\in G$ and $[\xi,x]\in\mathrm{Ind}_{\iota}X$.
Definition 5.12. Let $G\!\curvearrowright\!X$ and $H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$ be any pair of 0-cells in $\mathbb{S}$. Then a 2-category $\mathrm{Span}^{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}_{H\!\curvearrowright\!Y}$ is defined as follows. (0) A 0-cell in $\mathrm{Span}^{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}_{H\!\curvearrowright\!Y}$ is a span $S$ to $G\!\curvearrowright\!X$ from $H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$. (1) A 1-cell in $\mathrm{Span}^{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}_{H\!\curvearrowright\!Y}$ from $S=(G\!\curvearrowright\!X\overset{\alpha_{S}}{\longleftarrow}L_{S}\!% \curvearrowright\!W_{S}\overset{\beta_{S}}{\longrightarrow}H\!\curvearrowright% \!Y)$ to $T=(G\!\curvearrowright\!X\overset{\alpha_{T}}{\longleftarrow}L_{T}\!% \curvearrowright\!W_{T}\overset{\beta_{T}}{\longrightarrow}H\!\curvearrowright% \!Y)$ is a triplet $(\varphi,\mu_{X},\mu_{Y})$ of a 1-cell $\varphi$ and 2-cells $\mu_{X},\mu_{Y}$ in $\mathbb{S}$ as in the following diagram. $\xy(-20,0)*+{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}="0";(0,10)*+{L_{S}\!\curvearrowright\!W_{% S}}="2";(0,-10)*+{L_{T}\!\curvearrowright\!W_{T}}="4";(20,0)*+{H\!% \curvearrowright\!Y}="6";{\ar_{\alpha_{S}}"2";"0"};{\ar^{\beta_{S}}"2";"6"};{% \ar^{\varphi}"2";"4"};{\ar^{\alpha_{T}}"4";"0"};{\ar_{\beta_{T}}"4";"6"};{\ar@% {=>}^{\mu_{X}}(-4,-2);(-8,2)};{\ar@{=>}_{\mu_{Y}}(4,-2);(8,2)};\endxy$ (2) If $(\varphi,\mu_{X},\mu_{Y})\colon S\to T$ and $(\varphi^{\prime},\mu_{X}^{\prime},\mu_{Y}^{\prime})\colon S\to T$ are 1-cells in $\mathrm{Span}^{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}_{H\!\curvearrowright\!Y}$, then a 2-cell $\varepsilon\colon(\varphi,\mu_{X},\mu_{Y})\Rightarrow(\varphi^{\prime},\mu_{X}% ^{\prime},\mu_{Y}^{\prime})$ in $\mathrm{Span}^{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}_{H\!\curvearrowright\!Y}$ is a 2-cell $\varepsilon\colon\varphi\Rightarrow\varphi^{\prime}$ in $\mathbb{S}$, which makes the following diagrams commutative. $\xy(-10,6)*+{\alpha_{T}\circ\varphi}="0";(10,6)*+{\alpha_{T}\circ\varphi^{% \prime}}="2";(0,-8)*+{\alpha_{S}}="4";(0,10)*+{}="5";{\ar@{=>}^{\alpha_{T}% \circ\varepsilon}"0";"2"};{\ar@{=>}_{(}0.4){\mu_{X}}"0";"4"};{\ar@{=>}^{(}0.4)% {\mu_{X}^{\prime}}"2";"4"};{\ar@{}|\circlearrowright"4";"5"};\endxy,\qquad\xy(% -10,6)*+{\beta_{T}\circ\varphi}="0";(10,6)*+{\beta_{T}\circ\varphi^{\prime}}="% 2";(0,-8)*+{\beta_{S}}="4";(0,10)*+{}="5";{\ar@{=>}^{\beta_{T}\circ\varepsilon% }"0";"2"};{\ar@{=>}_{(}0.4){\mu_{Y}}"0";"4"};{\ar@{=>}^{(}0.4){\mu_{Y}^{\prime% }}"2";"4"};{\ar@{}|\circlearrowright"4";"5"};\endxy$ Composition of 1-cells $(\varphi,\mu_{X},\mu_{Y})\colon(G\!\curvearrowright\!X\overset{\alpha_{S}}{% \longleftarrow}L_{S}\!\curvearrowright\!W_{S}\overset{\beta_{S}}{% \longrightarrow}H\!\curvearrowright\!Y)\to(G\!\curvearrowright\!X\overset{% \alpha_{T}}{\longleftarrow}L_{T}\!\curvearrowright\!W_{T}\overset{\beta_{T}}{% \longrightarrow}H\!\curvearrowright\!Y)$ and $(\psi,\nu_{X},\nu_{Y})\colon(G\!\curvearrowright\!X\overset{\alpha_{T}}{% \longleftarrow}L_{T}\!\curvearrowright\!W_{T}\overset{\beta_{T}}{% \longrightarrow}H\!\curvearrowright\!Y)\to(G\!\curvearrowright\!X\overset{% \alpha_{P}}{\longleftarrow}L_{P}\!\curvearrowright\!W_{P}\overset{\beta_{P}}{% \longrightarrow}H\!\curvearrowright\!Y)$ is defined to be $(\psi\circ\varphi,\mu_{X}\cdot(\nu_{X}\circ\varphi),\mu_{Y}\cdot(\nu_{Y}\circ% \varphi)).$ Vertical composition of 2-cells $\xy(-20,0)*+{S}="0";(20,0)*+{T}="2";{\ar@/^{2}.0pc/^{(\varphi,\mu_{X},\mu_{Y})% }"0";"2"};{\ar|*+{{}_{(\varphi^{\prime},\mu_{X}^{\prime},\mu_{Y}^{\prime})}}"0% ";"2"};{\ar@/_{2}.0pc/_{(\varphi^{\prime\prime},\mu_{X}^{\prime\prime},\mu_{Y}% ^{\prime\prime})}"0";"2"};{\ar@{=>}^{\varepsilon}(0,6);(0,3)};{\ar@{=>}^{% \varepsilon^{\prime}}(0,-3);(0,-6)};\endxy$ is defined to be $\varepsilon^{\prime}\cdot\varepsilon$, using the vertical composition in $\mathbb{S}$. Horizontal composition of 2-cells $\xy(-36,0)*+{S}="0";(0,0)*+{T}="2";(36,0)*+{P}="4";{\ar@/^{1}.4pc/^{(\varphi,% \mu_{X},\mu_{Y})}"0";"2"};{\ar@/_{1}.4pc/_{(\varphi^{\prime},\mu_{X}^{\prime},% \mu_{Y}^{\prime})}"0";"2"};{\ar@/^{1}.4pc/^{(\psi,\nu_{X},\nu_{Y})}"2";"4"};{% \ar@/_{1}.4pc/_{(\psi^{\prime},\nu_{X}^{\prime},\nu_{Y}^{\prime})}"2";"4"};{% \ar@{=>}^{\varepsilon}(-18,2);(-18,-2)};{\ar@{=>}^{\delta}(18,2);(18,-2)};\endxy$ is defined to be $\delta\circ\varepsilon$, using the horizontal composition in $\mathbb{S}$.
Definition 6.23. Let $G\!\curvearrowright\!X,H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$ be 1-cells. Let $x_{1},\ldots,x_{s}\in X$ and $y_{1},\ldots,y_{t}\in Y$ be complete sets of representatives of orbits of $X$ and $Y$. For any span $S$ to $H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$ from $G\!\curvearrowright\!X$, for any $1\leq i\leq s$ and $1\leq j\leq t$, define a (class of) span $\Gamma_{ji}^{(S)}$ to $H_{y_{j}}\!\curvearrowright\!\mathrm{pt}$ from $G_{x_{i}}\!\curvearrowright\!\mathrm{pt}$ by $\Gamma_{ji}^{(S)}=\mathbf{R}_{\eta_{j}^{(Y)}}\circ[S]\circ\mathbf{T}_{\eta_{i}% ^{(X)}}.$
Definition 2.1. The category $\mathrm{GrSet}$ is defined as follows. (1) An object in $\mathrm{GrSet}$ is a pair of a finite group $G$ and a finite $G$-set $X$. We denote this pair by $G\!\curvearrowright\!X$. (2) If $G\!\curvearrowright\!X$ and $H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$ are two objects in $\mathrm{GrSet}$, then a morphism $\theta\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha\colon G\!\curvearrowright\!X\to H\!% \curvearrowright\!Y$ is a pair of a map $\alpha\colon X\to Y$ and a map $\theta\colon X\to\mathrm{Map}(G,H)\ ;\ x\mapsto\theta_{x}$ (namely, $\theta$ is a family of maps $\{\theta_{x}\}_{x\in X}$) satisfying (i) $\alpha(gx)=\theta_{x}(g)\alpha(x)$ (ii) $\theta_{x}(gg^{\prime})=\theta_{g^{\prime}x}\theta_{x}(g^{\prime})$ for any $x\in X$ and any $g,g^{\prime}\in G$. $\theta$ is called the acting part of $\theta\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha$. For any consecutive pair of morphisms $G\!\curvearrowright\!X\overset{\theta\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha}{% \longrightarrow}H\!\curvearrowright\!Y\overset{\tau\!\curvearrowright\!\beta}{% \longrightarrow}K\!\curvearrowright\!Z,$ we define their composition $(\tau\!\curvearrowright\!\beta)\circ(\theta\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha)=\tau% \circ\theta\!\curvearrowright\!\beta\circ\alpha$ by - $\beta\circ\alpha\colon X\to Z$ is the usual composition of maps of sets, - $\tau\circ\theta$ is defined by $(\tau\circ\theta)_{x}(g)=\tau_{\alpha(x)}(\theta_{x}(g))\quad(\forall g\in G),$ namely, $(\tau\circ\theta)_{x}=\tau_{\alpha(x)}\circ\theta_{x}$ for any $x\in X$. This $\tau\circ\theta\!\curvearrowright\!\beta\circ\alpha\colon G\!\curvearrowright% \!X\to H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$ becomes in fact a morphism, since we have $\displaystyle\quad\beta\circ\alpha(gx)$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle\beta(\theta_{x}(g)\alpha(x))$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle\tau_{\alpha(x)}(\theta_{x}(g))\beta\circ\alpha(x)\ =\ (\tau\circ% \theta)_{x}\cdot(\beta\circ\alpha(x)),$ $\displaystyle(\tau\circ\theta)_{x}(gg^{\prime})$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle\tau_{\alpha(x)}(\theta_{x}(gg^{\prime}))\ =\ \tau_{\alpha(x)}(% \theta_{g^{\prime}x}(g)\theta_{x}(g^{\prime}))$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle\tau_{\theta_{x}(g^{\prime})\alpha(x)}(\theta_{g^{\prime}x}(g))% \cdot\tau_{\alpha(x)}(\theta_{x}(g^{\prime}))$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle(\tau\circ\theta)_{g^{\prime}x}(g)\cdot(\tau\circ\theta)_{x}(g^{% \prime})$ for any $x\in X$ and any $g,g^{\prime}\in G$.
Definition 2.8. Let $\theta\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha,\theta^{\prime}\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha^{% \prime}\colon G\!\curvearrowright\!X\to H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$ be any pair of 1-cells. A 2-cell $\varepsilon\colon\theta\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha\Rightarrow\theta^{\prime}\!% \curvearrowright\!\alpha^{\prime}$ is a map $\varepsilon\colon X\to H\ ;\ x\mapsto\varepsilon_{x}$ satisfying (i) $\alpha^{\prime}(x)=\varepsilon_{x}\alpha(x)$, (ii) $\varepsilon_{gx}\theta_{x}(g)\varepsilon_{x}^{-1}=\theta^{\prime}_{x}(g)$ for any $x\in X$ and $g\in G$. If we are given a consecutive pair of 2-cells $\xy(-12,0)*+{X}="0";(12,0)*+{Y}="2";{\ar@/^{2}.0pc/^{\theta\!\curvearrowright% \!\alpha}"0";"2"};{\ar|*+{{}_{\theta^{\prime}\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha^{% \prime}}}"0";"2"};{\ar@/_{2}.0pc/_{\theta^{\prime\prime}\!\curvearrowright\!% \alpha^{\prime\prime}}"0";"2"};{\ar@{=>}^{\varepsilon}(0,6);(0,3)};{\ar@{=>}^{% \varepsilon^{\prime}}(0,-3);(0,-6)};\endxy$ then their vertical composition $\varepsilon^{\prime}\cdot\varepsilon\colon\theta\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha% \Rightarrow\theta^{\prime\prime}\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha^{\prime\prime}$ is defined by $(\varepsilon^{\prime}\cdot\varepsilon)_{x}=\varepsilon^{\prime}_{x}\varepsilon% _{x}\quad(\forall x\in X).$ This becomes indeed a 2-cell, since we have $\alpha^{\prime\prime}(x)=\varepsilon^{\prime}_{x}\alpha(x)=\varepsilon^{\prime% }_{x}\varepsilon_{x}\alpha(x),$ $\varepsilon^{\prime}_{gx}\varepsilon_{gx}\theta_{x}(g)\varepsilon_{x}^{-1}% \varepsilon^{\prime-1}_{x}=\varepsilon^{\prime}_{gx}\theta^{\prime}_{x}(g)% \varepsilon^{\prime-1}_{x}=\theta^{\prime\prime}_{x}(g)$ for any $x\in X$ and $g\in G$. Associativity of this vertical composition is trivially satisfied. The identity 2-cell $\mathrm{id}\colon\mathrm{id}_{\theta\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha}\Rightarrow% \mathrm{id}_{\theta\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha}$ is given by $\mathrm{id}_{x}=e\ (\forall x\in X)$.
Definition 5.2. A semi-Mackey functor $M=(M^{\ast},M_{\ast})$ on $\mathbb{S}$ is a pair of a contravariant 2-functor $M^{\ast}\colon\mathbb{S}\to\mathit{Set}$ and a covariant 2-functor $M_{\ast}\colon\mathbb{S}\to\mathit{Set}$ which satisfies the following. (0) $M^{\ast}(G\!\curvearrowright\!X)=M_{\ast}(G\!\curvearrowright\!X)$ for any 0-cell $G\!\curvearrowright\!X\in\mathbb{S}^{0}$. We denote this simply by $M(G\!\curvearrowright\!X)$. (1) [Additivity] For any pair of 0-cells $G\!\curvearrowright\!X$ and $H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$ in $\mathbb{S}$, if we take their 2-coproduct $G\!\curvearrowright\!X\overset{\upsilon_{X}}{\longrightarrow}G\!% \curvearrowright\!X\amalg H\!\curvearrowright\!Y\overset{\upsilon_{Y}}{% \longleftarrow}H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$ in $\mathbb{S}$, then the natural map $(M^{\ast}(\upsilon_{X}),M^{\ast}(\upsilon_{Y}))\colon M(G\!\curvearrowright\!X% \amalg H\!\curvearrowright\!Y)\to M(G\!\curvearrowright\!X)\times M(H\!% \curvearrowright\!Y)$ is bijective. (2) [Mackey condition] For any 2-fibered product $\xy(-10,7)*+{L\!\curvearrowright\!W}="0";(10,7)*+{H\!\curvearrowright\!Y}="2";% (-10,-7)*+{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}="4";(10,-7)*+{K\!\curvearrowright\!Z}="6";{% \ar^{\delta}"0";"2"};{\ar_{\gamma}"0";"4"};{\ar^{\beta}"2";"6"};{\ar_{\alpha}"% 4";"6"};{\ar@{=>}^{\kappa}(-2,0);(2,0)};\endxy$ in $\mathbb{S}$, the following diagram in $\mathit{Set}$ becomes commutative. $\xy(-14,8)*+{M(L\!\curvearrowright\!W)}="0";(14,8)*+{M(H\!\curvearrowright\!Y)% }="2";(-14,-8)*+{M(G\!\curvearrowright\!X)}="4";(14,-8)*+{M(K\!% \curvearrowright\!Z)}="6";{\ar_{M^{\ast}(\delta)}"2";"0"};{\ar_{M_{\ast}(% \gamma)}"0";"4"};{\ar^{M_{\ast}(\beta)}"2";"6"};{\ar^{M^{\ast}(\alpha)}"6";"4"% };{\ar@{}|\circlearrowright"0";"6"};\endxy$
Definition 6.4. Let $S=(G\!\curvearrowright\!X\overset{\alpha_{S}}{\longleftarrow}L_{S}\!% \curvearrowright\!W_{S}\overset{\beta_{S}}{\longrightarrow}H\!\curvearrowright% \!Y)$ be any span in $\mathbb{S}$. By Corollary 3.15, we obtain a 1-cell $\gamma_{S}\colon L_{S}\!\curvearrowright\!W_{S}\to G\times H\!\curvearrowright% \!X\times Y$ defined by $\displaystyle\gamma_{S}(w)=(\alpha_{S}(w),\beta_{S}(w))$ $\displaystyle(\forall w\in W_{S}),$ $\displaystyle\theta_{\gamma_{S},w}(\ell)=(\theta_{\alpha_{S}w}(\ell),\theta_{% \beta_{S},w}(\ell))$ $\displaystyle(\forall w\in W_{S},\forall\ell\in L_{S}).$ Then the range of $S$ is defined to be $R(S)=\mathrm{SIm}\gamma_{S}=(G\times H\times W_{S})/\sim,$ regarded as a $G$-$H$-biset by $\displaystyle g[\xi,\eta,w]h$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle(g,h^{-1})[\xi,\eta,w]$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle[g\xi,h^{-1}\eta,w]\qquad(\forall g\in G,\forall h\in H,\forall[% \xi,\eta,w]\in R(S)).$
Definition 5.4. Let $M$ and $N$ be semi-Mackey functors on $\mathbb{S}$. A morphism $\varphi\colon M\to N$ of semi-Mackey functors is a family of maps $\varphi=\{\varphi_{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}\colon M(G\!\curvearrowright\!X)\to N% (G\!\curvearrowright\!X)\}_{G\!\curvearrowright\!X\in\mathbb{S}^{0}}$ which forms natural transformations $\varphi\colon M^{\ast}\Rightarrow N^{\ast}\ \ \ \text{and}\ \ \ \varphi\colon M% _{\ast}\Rightarrow N_{\ast}.$ With the usual composition of natural transformations, we obtain the category of semi-Mackey functors denoted by $\mathit{SMack}(\mathbb{S})$.
Definition . $\mathcal{B}$ is defined as follows. (1) An object in $\mathcal{B}$ is a finite group. (2) For objects $G,H$ in $\mathcal{B}$, consider a set of the isomorphism classes of finite $H$-$G$-bisets. This forms a commutative monoid with addition $\amalg$ and unit $\emptyset$, and thus we can take its additive completion $\mathcal{B}(G,H)$. This is the set of morphisms from $G$ to $H$ in $\mathcal{B}$. A $H$-$G$-biset $U$ is written as ${}_{H}U_{G}$. The composition of two consecutive bisets ${}_{H}U_{G}$ and ${}_{K}V_{H}$ is given by $V\times_{H}U=(V\times U)/\sim,$ where the equivalence relation is defined as - $(v,u),(v^{\prime},u^{\prime})\in V\times U$ are equivalent if there exists $h\in H$ satisfying $v=v^{\prime}h$ and $u^{\prime}=hu$. This defines the composition of morphisms in $\mathcal{B}$, by linearity.
Definition 5.19. The span category $\mathrm{Sp}$ of $\mathbb{S}$ is defined as follows. (1) $\mathrm{Ob}(\mathrm{Sp})=\mathbb{S}^{0}=\mathrm{Ob}(\mathscr{C})$. (2) For any pair of objects $G\!\curvearrowright\!X$ and $H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$, a morphism from $G\!\curvearrowright\!X$ to $H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$ is a equivalence class $[S]$ of a span ${}_{H\!\curvearrowright\!Y}S_{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}\in(\mathrm{Span}^{H\!% \curvearrowright\!Y}_{G\!\curvearrowright\!X})^{0}$. When we want to emphasize it is a morphism in $\mathrm{Sp}$, we will denote it by $[S]\colon G\!\curvearrowright\!X\rightharpoonup H\!\curvearrowright\!Y.$ The composition of morphisms is defined by the composition of spans, and the identity span gives the identity morphism.
Definition 3.18. A weak fibered product in $\mathscr{C}$ $\xy(-10,6)*+{L\!\curvearrowright\!W}="0";(10,6)*+{H\!\curvearrowright\!Y}="2";% (-10,-6)*+{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}="4";(10,-6)*+{K\!\curvearrowright\!Z}="6";{% \ar^{\underline{\delta}}"0";"2"};{\ar_{\underline{\gamma}}"0";"4"};{\ar^{% \underline{\beta}}"2";"6"};{\ar_{\underline{\alpha}}"4";"6"};{\ar@{}|% \circlearrowright"0";"6"};\endxy$ is called a natural weak pullback (of $\underline{\alpha}$ and $\underline{\beta}$) if it comes from some 2-fibered product in $\mathbb{S}$. We write as $\xy(-10,6)*+{L\!\curvearrowright\!W}="0";(10,6)*+{H\!\curvearrowright\!Y}="2";% (-10,-6)*+{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}="4";(10,-6)*+{K\!\curvearrowright\!Z}="6";(% 0,0)*+{\mathrm{nwp}}="10";{\ar^{\underline{\delta}}"0";"2"};{\ar_{\underline{% \gamma}}"0";"4"};{\ar^{\underline{\beta}}"2";"6"};{\ar_{\underline{\alpha}}"4"% ;"6"};\endxy$ to indicate it is a natural weak pullback.
Definition 5.27. A semi-Mackey functor $M$ on $\mathbb{S}$ is called deflative if for any stab-surjective 1-cell $\alpha\colon G\!\curvearrowright\!X\to H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$ in $\mathbb{S}$, the equality $M_{\ast}(\alpha)\circ M^{\ast}(\alpha)=\mathrm{id}_{M(H\!\curvearrowright\!Y)}$ is satisfied. A Mackey functor is called deflative if it is deflative as a semi-Mackey functor. The full subcategory of deflative semi-Mackey functors is denoted by $\mathit{SMack}_{\mathrm{dfl}}(\mathbb{S})\subseteq\mathit{SMack}(\mathbb{S})$. Similarly, the full subcategory of deflative Mackey functors is denoted by $\mathit{Mack}_{\mathrm{dfl}}(\mathbb{S})\subseteq\mathit{Mack}(\mathbb{S})$.
Definition 5.13. Let $G\!\curvearrowright\!X$ and $H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$ be 0-cells in $\mathbb{S}$. Two spans $\displaystyle S=(G\!\curvearrowright\!X\overset{\alpha_{S}}{\longleftarrow}L_{% S}\!\curvearrowright\!W_{S}\overset{\beta_{S}}{\longrightarrow}H\!% \curvearrowright\!Y),$ $\displaystyle T=(G\!\curvearrowright\!X\overset{\alpha_{T}}{\longleftarrow}L_{% T}\!\curvearrowright\!W_{T}\overset{\beta_{T}}{\longrightarrow}H\!% \curvearrowright\!Y)$ are equivalent if there exists an adjoint equivalence $\xy(-20,0)*+{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}="0";(0,10)*+{L_{S}\!\curvearrowright\!W_{% S}}="2";(0,-10)*+{L_{T}\!\curvearrowright\!W_{T}}="4";(20,0)*+{H\!% \curvearrowright\!Y}="6";{\ar_{\alpha_{S}}"2";"0"};{\ar^{\beta_{S}}"2";"6"};{% \ar^{\varphi}"2";"4"};{\ar^{\alpha_{T}}"4";"0"};{\ar_{\beta_{T}}"4";"6"};{\ar@% {=>}^{\nu_{X}}(-4,-2);(-8,2)};{\ar@{=>}_{\nu_{Y}}(4,-2);(8,2)};\endxy$ in $\mathrm{Span}^{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}_{H\!\curvearrowright\!Y}$. Remark that this implies in particular $\varphi$ is an adjoint equivalence in $\mathbb{S}$. We denote the equivalence class of $S$ by $[S]$.
Definition 2.15. 2-category $\mathbb{S}$ is defined as follows. (0) $\mathbb{S}^{0}=\mathrm{Ob}(\mathrm{GrSet})$. (1) For any 0-cells $G\!\curvearrowright\!X$ and $H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$, $\mathbb{S}^{1}(G\!\curvearrowright\!X,H\!\curvearrowright\!Y)=\mathrm{GrSet}(G% \!\curvearrowright\!X,H\!\curvearrowright\!Y).$ (2) For any 1-cells $\theta\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha,\theta^{\prime}\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha^{% \prime}\colon G\!\curvearrowright\!X\to H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$, 2-cells $\varepsilon\colon\theta\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha\Rightarrow\theta^{\prime}\!% \curvearrowright\!\alpha^{\prime}$ are those defined in Definition 2.8. Thus any 2-cell in $\mathbb{S}$ is invertible with respect to the vertical composition.
Definition 5.1. A semi-Mackey functor $M=(M^{\ast},M_{\ast})$ on $\mathscr{C}$ is a pair of a contravariant functor $M^{\ast}\colon\mathscr{C}\to\mathit{Set}$ and a covariant functor $M_{\ast}\colon\mathscr{C}\to\mathit{Set}$ which satisfies the following. (0) $M^{\ast}(G\!\curvearrowright\!X)=M_{\ast}(G\!\curvearrowright\!X)$ for any object $G\!\curvearrowright\!X\in\mathrm{Ob}(\mathscr{C})$. We denote this simply by $M(G\!\curvearrowright\!X)$. (1) [Additivity] For any pair of objects $G\!\curvearrowright\!X$ and $H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$ in $\mathscr{C}$, if we take their coproduct $G\!\curvearrowright\!X\overset{\underline{\upsilon_{X}}}{\longrightarrow}G\!% \curvearrowright\!X\amalg H\!\curvearrowright\!Y\overset{\underline{\upsilon_{% Y}}}{\longleftarrow}H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$ in $\mathscr{C}$, then the natural map $(M^{\ast}(\underline{\upsilon_{X}}),M^{\ast}(\underline{\upsilon_{Y}}))\colon M% (G\!\curvearrowright\!X\amalg H\!\curvearrowright\!Y)\to M(G\!\curvearrowright% \!X)\times M(H\!\curvearrowright\!Y)$ is bijective. (2) [Mackey condition] For any natural weak pullback $\xy(-10,7)*+{L\!\curvearrowright\!W}="0";(10,7)*+{H\!\curvearrowright\!Y}="2";% (-10,-7)*+{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}="4";(10,-7)*+{K\!\curvearrowright\!Z}="6";(% 0,0)*+{\mathrm{nwp}}="10";{\ar^{\underline{\delta}}"0";"2"};{\ar_{\underline{% \gamma}}"0";"4"};{\ar^{\underline{\beta}}"2";"6"};{\ar_{\underline{\alpha}}"4"% ;"6"};\endxy$ in $\mathscr{C}$, the following diagram in $\mathit{Set}$ becomes commutative. $\xy(-14,8)*+{M(L\!\curvearrowright\!W)}="0";(14,8)*+{M(H\!\curvearrowright\!Y)% }="2";(-14,-8)*+{M(G\!\curvearrowright\!X)}="4";(14,-8)*+{M(K\!% \curvearrowright\!Z)}="6";{\ar_{M^{\ast}(\underline{\delta})}"2";"0"};{\ar_{M_% {\ast}(\underline{\gamma})}"0";"4"};{\ar^{M_{\ast}(\underline{\beta})}"2";"6"}% ;{\ar^{M^{\ast}(\underline{\alpha})}"6";"4"};{\ar@{}|\circlearrowright"0";"6"};\endxy$
Definition 5.32. Let $G\!\curvearrowright\!X$ be any 0-cell in $\mathbb{S}$. Then a 2-category $\mathbb{S}/_{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}$ is defined as follows. (0) A 0-cell in $\mathbb{S}/_{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}$ is a 1-cell $(K\!\curvearrowright\!A\overset{\alpha}{\longrightarrow}G\!\curvearrowright\!X)$ in $\mathbb{S}$, from some $K\!\curvearrowright\!A\in\mathbb{S}^{0}$. (1) A 1-cell in $\mathbb{S}/_{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}$ from $(K\!\curvearrowright\!A\overset{\alpha}{\longrightarrow}G\!\curvearrowright\!X)$ to $(H\!\curvearrowright\!B\overset{\beta}{\longrightarrow}G\!\curvearrowright\!X)$ is a pair $(\varphi,\mu)$ of a 1-cell $\varphi$ and a 2-cell $\mu$ in $\mathbb{S}$ as in the following diagram. $\xy(-10,6)*+{K\!\curvearrowright\!A}="0";(10,6)*+{H\!\curvearrowright\!B}="2";% (0,-8)*+{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}="4";{\ar^{\varphi}"0";"2"};{\ar_{(}0.4){% \alpha}"0";"4"};{\ar^{(}0.38){\beta}"2";"4"};{\ar@{=>}^{\mu}(2,3);(-2,0)};\endxy$ (2) If $(\varphi,\mu)\colon(K\!\curvearrowright\!A\overset{\alpha}{\longrightarrow}G\!% \curvearrowright\!X)\to(H\!\curvearrowright\!B\overset{\beta}{\longrightarrow}% G\!\curvearrowright\!X)$ and $(\varphi^{\prime},\mu^{\prime})\colon(K\!\curvearrowright\!A\overset{\alpha}{% \longrightarrow}G\!\curvearrowright\!X)\to(H\!\curvearrowright\!B\overset{% \beta}{\longrightarrow}G\!\curvearrowright\!X)$ are 1-cells in $\mathbb{S}/_{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}$, then a 2-cell $\varepsilon\colon(\varphi,\mu)\Rightarrow(\varphi^{\prime},\mu^{\prime})$ in $\mathbb{S}/_{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}$ is a 2-cell $\varepsilon\colon\varphi\Rightarrow\varphi^{\prime}$ in $\mathbb{S}$, which makes the following diagram commutative. $\xy(-10,6)*+{\beta\circ\varphi}="0";(10,6)*+{\beta\circ\varphi^{\prime}}="2";(% 0,-8)*+{\alpha}="4";(0,10)*+{}="5";{\ar@{=>}^{\beta\circ\varepsilon}"0";"2"};{% \ar@{=>}_{(}0.4){\mu}"0";"4"};{\ar@{=>}^{(}0.4){\mu^{\prime}}"2";"4"};{\ar@{}|% \circlearrowright"4";"5"};\endxy$ Composition of 1-cells $(K\!\curvearrowright\!A\overset{\alpha}{\longrightarrow}G\!\curvearrowright\!X% )\overset{(\varphi,\mu)}{\longrightarrow}(H\!\curvearrowright\!B\overset{\beta% }{\longrightarrow}G\!\curvearrowright\!X)\overset{(\psi,\nu)}{\longrightarrow}% (L\!\curvearrowright\!C\overset{\gamma}{\longrightarrow}G\!\curvearrowright\!X)$ is defined to be $(\psi\circ\varphi,\mu\cdot(\nu\circ\varphi))\colon(K\!\curvearrowright\!A% \overset{\alpha}{\longrightarrow}G\!\curvearrowright\!X)\to(L\!% \curvearrowright\!C\overset{\gamma}{\longrightarrow}G\!\curvearrowright\!X).$ Vertical composition of 2-cells $\xy(-26,0)*+{(K\!\curvearrowright\!A\overset{\alpha}{\longrightarrow}G\!% \curvearrowright\!X)}="0";(26,0)*+{(H\!\curvearrowright\!B\overset{\beta}{% \longrightarrow}G\!\curvearrowright\!X)}="2";{\ar@/^{2}.0pc/^{(\varphi,\mu)}"0% ";"2"};{\ar|*+{{}_{(\varphi^{\prime},\mu^{\prime})}}"0";"2"};{\ar@/_{2}.0pc/_{% (\varphi^{\prime\prime},\mu^{\prime\prime})}"0";"2"};{\ar@{=>}^{\varepsilon}(0% ,6);(0,3)};{\ar@{=>}^{\varepsilon^{\prime}}(0,-3);(0,-6)};\endxy$ is defined to be $\varepsilon^{\prime}\cdot\varepsilon$, using the vertical composition in $\mathbb{S}$. Horizontal composition of 2-cells $\xy(-44,0)*+{(K\!\curvearrowright\!A\overset{\alpha}{\longrightarrow}G\!% \curvearrowright\!X)}="0";(0,0)*+{(H\!\curvearrowright\!B\overset{\beta}{% \longrightarrow}G\!\curvearrowright\!X)}="2";(44,0)*+{(L\!\curvearrowright\!C% \overset{\gamma}{\longrightarrow}G\!\curvearrowright\!X)}="4";{\ar@/^{1}.6pc/^% {(\varphi,\mu)}"0";"2"};{\ar@/_{1}.6pc/_{(\varphi^{\prime},\mu^{\prime})}"0";"% 2"};{\ar@/^{1}.6pc/^{(\psi,\nu)}"2";"4"};{\ar@/_{1}.6pc/_{(\psi^{\prime},\nu^{% \prime})}"2";"4"};{\ar@{=>}^{\varepsilon}(-22,2.5);(-22,-2.5)};{\ar@{=>}^{% \delta}(22,2.5);(22,-2.5)};\endxy$ is defined to be $\delta\circ\varepsilon$, using the horizontal composition in $\mathbb{S}$.
Definition 4.1. A 1-cell $\alpha\colon G\!\curvearrowright\!X\to H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$ is called surjective on stabilizers or shortly stab-surjective, if the following conditions are satisfied. (i) For any $y\in Y$, there exist $x\in X$ and $h\in H$ satisfying $y=h\alpha(x).$ (ii) If $x,x^{\prime}\in X$ and $h,h^{\prime}\in H$ satisfy $h\alpha(x)=h^{\prime}\alpha(x^{\prime})$, then there exists $g\in G$ which satisfies $x^{\prime}=gx\ \ \ \text{and}\ \ \ h=h^{\prime}\theta_{\alpha,x}(g).$
Definition 5.16. Let $G\!\curvearrowright\!X$ and $H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$ be 0-cells in $\mathbb{S}$. For spans in $\mathbb{S}$ $S=(G\!\curvearrowright\!X\overset{\alpha_{S}}{\longleftarrow}L_{S}\!% \curvearrowright\!W_{S}\overset{\beta_{S}}{\longrightarrow}H\!\curvearrowright% \!Y)$ and $T=(G\!\curvearrowright\!X\overset{\alpha_{T}}{\longleftarrow}L_{T}\!% \curvearrowright\!W_{T}\overset{\beta_{T}}{\longrightarrow}H\!\curvearrowright% \!Y),$ their sum is defined to be the 2-coproduct $S+T=(G\!\curvearrowright\!X\overset{\alpha_{S}\cup\alpha_{T}}{\longleftarrow}L% _{S}\!\curvearrowright\!W_{S}\amalg L_{T}\!\curvearrowright\!W_{T}\overset{% \beta_{S}\cup\beta_{T}}{\longrightarrow}H\!\curvearrowright\!Y).$
Definition 2.18. Category $\mathscr{C}$ is defined as follows. (i) $\mathrm{Ob}(\mathscr{C})=\mathbb{S}^{0}=\mathrm{Ob}(\mathrm{GrSet})$. (ii) For any pair of objects $G\!\curvearrowright\!X,H\!\curvearrowright\!Y\in\mathrm{Ob}(\mathscr{C})$, we define an equivalence relation on $\mathbb{S}^{1}(G\!\curvearrowright\!X,H\!\curvearrowright\!Y)$ as follows. - 1-cells $\theta\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha,\theta^{\prime}\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha^{% \prime}\in\mathbb{S}^{1}(G\!\curvearrowright\!X,H\!\curvearrowright\!Y)$ are equivalent if there exists some 2-cell $\varepsilon\colon\theta\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha\Rightarrow\theta^{\prime}\!% \curvearrowright\!\alpha^{\prime}$. The set of morphisms $\mathscr{C}(X,Y)$ is defined to be the quotient of $\mathbb{S}^{1}(G\!\curvearrowright\!X,H\!\curvearrowright\!Y)$ by this equivalence: $\mathscr{C}(X,Y)=\mathbb{S}^{1}(G\!\curvearrowright\!X,H\!\curvearrowright\!Y)% /\text{2-cells}$ The equivalence class of $\theta\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha$ is denoted by $\underline{\theta\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha}$, or simply by $\underline{\alpha}$. A general argument on 2-categories (with invertible 2-cells) shows that $\mathscr{C}$ becomes in fact a category. The composition of two consecutive morphisms $\underline{\theta\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha}\colon G\!\curvearrowright\!X\to H% \!\curvearrowright\!Y\ \ \text{and}\ \ \underline{\tau\!\curvearrowright\!% \beta}\colon H\!\curvearrowright\!Y\to K\!\curvearrowright\!Z$ is given by $\underline{\tau\!\curvearrowright\!\beta}\circ\underline{\theta\!% \curvearrowright\!\alpha}=\underline{(\tau\!\curvearrowright\!\beta)\circ(% \theta\!\curvearrowright\!\alpha)}=\underline{\tau\circ\theta\!% \curvearrowright\!\beta\circ\alpha}.$ Identity morphism for $G\!\curvearrowright\!X\in\mathrm{Ob}(\mathscr{C})$ is given by $\underline{\mathrm{id}_{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}}=\underline{\mathrm{id}_{G}\!% \curvearrowright\!\mathrm{id}_{X}}$.
Definition 5.11. Let $G\!\curvearrowright\!X$ and $H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$ be 0-cells in $\mathbb{S}$. A span $S$ to $G\!\curvearrowright\!X$ from $H\!\curvearrowright\!Y$ in $\mathbb{S}$ is a pair of 1-cells from some 0-cell $L_{S}\!\curvearrowright\!W_{S}$ $S=(G\!\curvearrowright\!X\overset{\alpha_{S}}{\longleftarrow}L_{S}\!% \curvearrowright\!W_{S}\overset{\beta_{S}}{\longrightarrow}H\!\curvearrowright% \!Y)$ in $\mathbb{S}$. We sometimes simply write this as ${}_{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}S_{H\!\curvearrowright\!Y}$. The span $(G\!\curvearrowright\!X\overset{\mathrm{id}_{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}}{% \longleftarrow}G\!\curvearrowright\!X\overset{\mathrm{id}_{G\!\curvearrowright% \!X}}{\longrightarrow}G\!\curvearrowright\!X)$ is denoted by $\mathrm{Id}={}_{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}\mathrm{Id}_{G\!\curvearrowright\!X}$, and called the identity span.
Definition 5.23. $\ \ $ (1) Denote the category of functors $E\colon\mathrm{Sp}\to\mathit{Set}$ preserving finite products by $\mathit{Add}(\mathrm{Sp},\mathit{Set})$. Morphisms are natural transformations. (2) Similarly, denote the category of functors $F\colon\mathcal{T}\to\mathit{Set}$ preserving finite products by $\mathit{Add}(\mathcal{T},\mathit{Set})$. Morphisms are natural transformations.
Definition 3.8. Let $\mathbb{C}$ be a 2-category with invertible 2-cells. For any $A_{1},A_{2},B\in\mathbb{C}^{0}$ and $f_{i}\in\mathbb{C}^{1}(A_{i},B)\ (i=1,2)$, 2-fibered product of $f_{1}$ and $f_{2}$ is defined to be a quartet $(A_{1}\times_{B}A_{2},\pi_{1},\pi_{2},\kappa)$ as in the diagram $\xy(-9,6)*+{A_{1}\times_{B}A_{2}}="0";(9,6)*+{A_{2}}="2";(-9,-6)*+{A_{1}}="4";% (9,-6)*+{B}="6";{\ar^{(}0.6){\pi_{2}}"0";"2"};{\ar_{\pi_{1}}"0";"4"};{\ar^{f_{% 2}}"2";"6"};{\ar_{f_{1}}"4";"6"};{\ar@{=>}_{\kappa}(-2,0);(2,0)};\endxy,$ which satisfies the following conditions. (i) For any diagram in $\mathbb{C}$ $\xy(-8,6)*+{X}="0";(8,6)*+{A_{2}}="2";(-8,-6)*+{A_{1}}="4";(8,-6)*+{B}="6";{% \ar^{g_{2}}"0";"2"};{\ar_{g_{1}}"0";"4"};{\ar^{f_{2}}"2";"6"};{\ar_{f_{1}}"4";% "6"};{\ar@{=>}^{\varepsilon}(-2,0);(2,0)};\endxy,$ there exist $g,\xi_{1},\xi_{2}$ as in the diagram $\xy(-22,16)*+{X}="-2";(-8,6)*+{A_{1}\times_{B}A_{2}}="0";(8,6)*+{A_{2}}="2";(-% 8,-7)*+{A_{1}}="4";(8,-7)*+{B}="6";{\ar^{g}"-2";"0"};{\ar@/^{1}.24pc/^{g_{2}}"% -2";"2"};{\ar@/_{1}.24pc/_{(}0.68){g_{1}}"-2";"4"};{\ar_{(}0.66){\pi_{2}}"0";"% 2"};{\ar^{\pi_{1}}"0";"4"};{\ar^{f_{2}}"2";"6"};{\ar_{f_{1}}"4";"6"};{\ar@{=>}% _{\kappa}(-1.5,-1);(2.5,-1)};{\ar@{=>}^{\xi_{1}}(-12,3);(-16,-1)};{\ar@{=>}_{% \xi_{2}}(-8,9);(-6,14)};\endxy,$ satisfying $\varepsilon\cdot(f_{1}\circ\xi_{1})=(f_{2}\circ\xi_{2})\cdot(\kappa\circ g)$, namely making the following diagram of 2-cells commutative. $\xy(-12,6)*+{f_{1}\circ\pi_{1}\circ g}="0";(12,6)*+{f_{2}\circ\pi_{2}\circ g}=% "2";(-12,-6)*+{f_{1}\circ g_{1}}="4";(12,-6)*+{f_{2}\circ g_{2}}="6";{\ar@{=>}% ^{\kappa\circ g}"0";"2"};{\ar@{=>}_{f_{1}\circ\xi_{1}}"0";"4"};{\ar@{=>}^{f_{2% }\circ\xi_{2}}"2";"6"};{\ar@{=>}_{\varepsilon}"4";"6"};{\ar@{}|% \circlearrowright"0";"6"};\endxy$ (ii) For any triplets $(g,\xi_{1},\xi_{2})$ and $(g^{\prime},\xi_{1}^{\prime},\xi_{2}^{\prime})$ as in (i), there exists a unique 2-cell $\zeta\in\mathbb{C}^{2}(g,g^{\prime})$ which satisfies $\xi^{\prime}\cdot(\pi_{i}\circ\zeta)=\xi_{i}\ (i=1,2)$.
